ugmented reality as soon as June=E2=80=A6

The timing of the launch has been a source of tension since the project beg=
an in early 2016, according to multiple people familiar with Apple=E2=80=99=
s internal discussions. Apple=E2=80=99s operations team wanted to ship a =
=E2=80=9Cversion one=E2=80=9D product, a ski goggle-like headset that will =
allow users to watch immersive 3D video, perform interactive workouts or ch=
at with realistic avatars through a revamped FaceTime. But Apple=E2=80=99s =
famed industrial design team had cautioned patience, wanting to delay until=
 a more lightweight version of AR glasses became technically feasible. Most=
 in the tech industry expect that to take several more years. In deciding t=
o press ahead with a debut this year, Cook has sided with operations chief =
Jeff Williams, according to two people familiar with Apple=E2=80=99s decisi=
on-making, and overruled the early objections from Apple=E2=80=99s designer=
s to wait for the tech to catch up with their vision.

I found the overall premise of this Article, particularly the alleged need =
for Cook to secure his legacy, to be a bit silly; my Dithering co-host John=
 Gruber explained why on Daring Fireball ( https://daringfireball.net/2023/=
03/to_ship_or_not_to_ship_headset_edition ). At the same time, Gruber has c=
onsistently raised the question as to what a mixed-reality headset would be=
 good for ( https://daringfireball.net/2023/01/information_apple_headset ) =
:

This headset project is very much real and, I believe, very much shipping t=
his year. But the fundamental question remains: What=E2=80=99s the point? T=
hink back to Steve Jobs=E2=80=99s presentation announcing the original iPad=
=E2=80=89=E2=80=94=E2=80=89the nut of the whole keynote was Jobs explaining=
 where the iPad might fit between an iPhone and MacBook. If it didn=E2=80=
=99t serve some tasks not just a little but a lot better than either an iPh=
one or Mac, there was no point to the iPad. The same is true for this heads=
et. And if it costs $3,000 and/or requires a tethered battery strapped arou=
nd your waist, the =E2=80=9Cthis better be an awesome experience=E2=80=9D b=
ar is raised even higher.

Dithering listeners know that I=E2=80=99m more intrigued by headsets than G=
ruber is, in part because of the concept of =E2=80=9Cpresence=E2=80=9D; my =
=E2=80=9Cah-ha=E2=80=9D moment came after the launch of Horizon Workrooms (=
